00:09:44.325 --> 00:09:45.710
And Gopi, you went
through that.

00:09:45.710 --> 00:09:47.826
How was that experience?

00:09:47.826 --> 00:09:48.324
GOPI KALLAYIL: Scary.

00:09:48.324 --> 00:09:49.320
Jumping off a cliff.

00:09:49.320 --> 00:09:49.850
JARED GORALNICK: Scary?

00:09:49.850 --> 00:09:50.440
And what happened?

00:09:50.440 --> 00:09:52.796
Did you land after you
got off the cliff?

00:09:52.796 --> 00:09:53.730
GOPI KALLAYIL: I survived.

00:09:53.730 --> 00:09:55.940
JARED GORALNICK: For a little
while, it feels quite amazing.

00:09:55.940 --> 00:09:58.590
And if you can maintain, it's
not that you need inbox zero,

00:09:58.590 --> 00:10:00.620
it's that you just don't want
to constantly be revisiting

00:10:00.620 --> 00:10:05.310
things and having that feeling
of not knowing what's next.

00:10:05.310 --> 00:10:07.870
And here's a picture up here.

00:10:07.870 --> 00:10:08.790
This is Suzanne here.

00:10:08.790 --> 00:10:11.200
This picture was
taken in 1985.

00:10:11.200 --> 00:10:12.250
She's pretty cute.

00:10:12.250 --> 00:10:14.770
I was all right back then when
I was four years old.

00:10:14.770 --> 00:10:17.370
But I have a feeling that
she has moved on.

00:10:17.370 --> 00:10:20.870
I know I have to sort of give
up on this opportunity here.

00:10:20.870 --> 00:10:23.220
And this message has been
uploaded all over

00:10:23.220 --> 00:10:24.150
the place by now.

00:10:24.150 --> 00:10:26.960
I think I can delete
it from my inbox.

00:10:26.960 --> 00:10:29.155
I think a lot of the reason why
we have so many messages

00:10:29.155 --> 00:10:31.980
is because we think there's
something we need to find.

00:10:31.980 --> 00:10:34.130
But we have tools to find it.

00:10:34.130 --> 00:10:37.040
So whether you're archiving or
you're deleting, you've got to

00:10:37.040 --> 00:10:38.590
move on from those messages.

00:10:38.590 --> 00:10:41.460
And I think you'll find yourself
so much more sane and

00:10:41.460 --> 00:10:44.500
so much more able to do things
that are remarkable.

00:10:44.500 --> 00:10:48.780
And I've already talked about
what enters into your inbox

00:10:48.780 --> 00:10:51.700
and what grabs your attention
from your mobile device or

00:10:51.700 --> 00:10:53.360
maybe some of you even
have pop-ups.

00:10:53.360 --> 00:10:55.940
Not in Outlook, but you might
have one of those Chrome

00:10:55.940 --> 00:10:58.650
extensions that shows you
when you get new mail.

00:10:58.650 --> 00:11:01.790
Turn those off and don't
continue to check email.

00:11:01.790 --> 00:11:05.100
I have spent much of my career
focused on this concept of

00:11:05.100 --> 00:11:06.390
interruptions.

00:11:06.390 --> 00:11:08.300
And that's what my product
does, AwayFind.

00:11:08.300 --> 00:11:11.490
I don't know if you're aware,
but we lose about four minutes

00:11:11.490 --> 00:11:14.790
to every interruption and the
rabbit hole it sends us down.

00:11:14.790 --> 00:11:16.600
Studies show that if you're
getting over 100 messages a

00:11:16.600 --> 00:11:20.405
day, that will turn into about
a quarter of your day is lost

00:11:20.405 --> 00:11:23.110
in interruptions and the time it
takes to get back on track.

00:11:23.110 --> 00:11:28.500
And the main step to fixing that
is closing your inbox,

00:11:28.500 --> 00:11:30.650
closing your Gmail
more of the day.

00:11:30.650 --> 00:11:34.000
You will never forget to check
it, I promise you.

00:11:34.000 --> 00:11:36.460
So close it, not just
during the holidays.

00:11:36.460 --> 00:11:38.340
And if you'd like to learn more
about that, you can go to

00:11:38.340 --> 00:11:39.250
awayfind.com.

00:11:39.250 --> 00:11:41.530
I don't know if you're allowed
to use my product at Google,

00:11:41.530 --> 00:11:43.910
but there is a guide to not
checking email that's been

00:11:43.910 --> 00:11:46.270
downloaded over 100,000 times.

00:11:46.270 --> 00:11:48.240
And that's just free as
part of our setup.

00:11:48.240 --> 00:11:49.280
And I hope it helps.

00:11:49.280 --> 00:11:52.570
It gives some more tactical
steps for this material.

00:11:52.570 --> 00:11:54.350
So that's it for email.

00:11:54.350 --> 00:11:58.460
Any quick questions about email
stuff before I jump on?

00:11:58.460 --> 00:12:00.260
We'll have a chance at the end
if you guys want to hear all

00:12:00.260 --> 00:12:02.930
my opinions about things
that could happen in

00:12:02.930 --> 00:12:05.320
change in that world.

00:12:05.320 --> 00:12:08.260
Second section here is
about productivity.

00:12:08.260 --> 00:12:12.330
And first off, those of you
that raised your hand with

00:12:12.330 --> 00:12:14.270
"Getting Things Done," you're
familiar with the mind like

00:12:14.270 --> 00:12:15.180
water metaphor?

00:12:15.180 --> 00:12:17.140
Anybody remember that,
mind like water?

00:12:17.140 --> 00:12:19.760
Great, is it something that's
been helpful to you?

00:12:19.760 --> 00:12:21.085
Have you ever applied that?

00:12:21.085 --> 00:12:21.570
AUDIENCE: I did.

00:12:21.570 --> 00:12:23.510
I sat still and made
a crazy long list.

00:12:23.510 --> 00:12:25.395
And I achieved mind like
water, and then I had

00:12:25.395 --> 00:12:27.007
a crazy long list.

00:12:27.007 --> 00:12:28.348
I didn't know what to do next.

00:12:28.348 --> 00:12:29.690
I'm hoping you can tell
me right now.

00:12:29.690 --> 00:12:31.220
JARED GORALNICK: I will
tell you right now.

00:12:31.220 --> 00:12:32.160
AUDIENCE: Right now.

00:12:32.160 --> 00:12:32.520
JARED GORALNICK: OK.

00:12:32.520 --> 00:12:35.010
So mind like water, it's the
concept that if you picture a

00:12:35.010 --> 00:12:38.750
little pond, and you picture a
rock falling into that pond,

00:12:38.750 --> 00:12:41.390
how does the pond respond?

00:12:41.390 --> 00:12:43.900
Exactly appropriately, it makes
little ripples at the

00:12:43.900 --> 00:12:46.240
angle, and weight, and momentum,
et cetera, based on

00:12:46.240 --> 00:12:47.660
how you dropped that
rock in there.

00:12:47.660 --> 00:12:50.170
Now picture yourself having
a harried day.

00:12:50.170 --> 00:12:52.120
Maybe this afternoon is going
to be particularly busy for

00:12:52.120 --> 00:12:53.860
you and you just crammed
this session in.

00:12:53.860 --> 00:12:56.160
And somebody comes to you
and says, you know what?

00:12:56.160 --> 00:12:58.650
There's this bug, and it's
actually live, and it's a

00:12:58.650 --> 00:12:59.780
really big issue.

00:12:59.780 --> 00:13:00.710
Now, how do you respond?

00:13:00.710 --> 00:13:03.210
Do you respond appropriately
by walking over to your

00:13:03.210 --> 00:13:04.940
terminal, looking at what's
going on, seeing how many

00:13:04.940 --> 00:13:05.330
people are doing it?

00:13:05.330 --> 00:13:08.060
Or do you flip out and scream
because you're thinking about

00:13:08.060 --> 00:13:10.100
the people you have to pick up
later today, you're thinking

00:13:10.100 --> 00:13:12.210
about the other tasks you have
to do, you're thinking about

00:13:12.210 --> 00:13:13.040
all this stuff going on?

00:13:13.040 --> 00:13:17.640
You are not like that rock
falling into the pond if you

00:13:17.640 --> 00:13:20.190
have all kinds of things
on your mind.

00:13:20.190 --> 00:13:22.930
So the goal of any productivity
system, anything,

00:13:22.930 --> 00:13:25.540
it doesn't matter, is to get
things out of your head and

00:13:25.540 --> 00:13:28.650
into a place that you can trust
so that when new things

00:13:28.650 --> 00:13:31.820
come at you, or when you get to
an item on your task list,

00:13:31.820 --> 00:13:35.270
you can actually focus on that
and not be overwhelmed by all

00:13:35.270 --> 00:13:36.380
that other stuff.

00:13:36.380 --> 00:13:40.050
Now, the first step to getting
things out of your head is

00:13:40.050 --> 00:13:41.790
putting it somewhere else.

00:13:41.790 --> 00:13:43.960
Now, you could put it
into Google Tasks.

00:13:43.960 --> 00:13:46.740
You could put it into some other
project management tool.

00:13:46.740 --> 00:13:49.560
But the main thing is just
getting it out of your head

00:13:49.560 --> 00:13:51.530
because the reality is you're
probably not going to get

00:13:51.530 --> 00:13:52.410
through all those things.

00:13:52.410 --> 00:13:54.980
But the first thing, the first
step, is to literally just

00:13:54.980 --> 00:13:55.930
write it all down.

00:13:55.930 --> 00:13:59.740
It's cathartic, it's liberating,
it's amazing, just

00:13:59.740 --> 00:14:00.780
getting it out of your head.

00:14:00.780 --> 00:14:02.190
Now, you're right, you're
going to end up with

00:14:02.190 --> 00:14:03.560
this big task list.

00:14:03.560 --> 00:14:06.590
And that might seem
overwhelming.

00:14:06.590 --> 00:14:08.900
But first off, you can at
least reorganize that as

00:14:08.900 --> 00:14:10.490
opposed to like your
inbox and whatnot.

00:14:10.490 --> 00:14:13.270
But second of all, you're going
to probably find that

00:14:13.270 --> 00:14:14.810
you'll never get to half
of your tasks.

00:14:14.810 --> 00:14:16.000
I mean, there are things
you have to do.

00:14:16.000 --> 00:14:17.380
There's a deadline, you
need to show up

00:14:17.380 --> 00:14:18.410
somewhere, or whatever.

00:14:18.410 --> 00:14:21.380
But there's a lot of tasks
you will never get to.

00:14:21.380 --> 00:14:22.690
And we have to accept that.

00:14:22.690 --> 00:14:24.810
We all in this room have to
accept that there is more in

00:14:24.810 --> 00:14:27.700
life that we want to
do than we will be

00:14:27.700 --> 00:14:29.200
able to actually do.

00:14:29.200 --> 00:14:31.440
But at least get it out of your
head and have it there in

00:14:31.440 --> 00:14:34.220
a bucket list, so maybe even
five years from now you will

00:14:34.220 --> 00:14:34.940
get back to it.

00:14:34.940 --> 00:14:37.300
Just get it out of your head,
and that's the first step.

00:14:37.300 --> 00:14:38.880
Knowing that is there
is totally fine.

00:14:38.880 --> 00:14:41.340
I recognize that I have a to-do
list for today that I

00:14:41.340 --> 00:14:43.870
actually care about and that I
have a giant list that's out

00:14:43.870 --> 00:14:46.100
of sight, out of mind, and maybe
that doesn't sound so

00:14:46.100 --> 00:14:49.120
good, but it feels a heck
of a lot better.

00:14:49.120 --> 00:14:51.750
So get yourself that
mind like water.

00:14:51.750 --> 00:14:54.670
And then, you guys are a company
that focuses on data.

00:14:54.670 --> 00:14:56.540
You have lots of things
you can measure.

00:14:56.540 --> 00:14:59.070
And now quantified self, we
have like seven different

00:14:59.070 --> 00:15:01.700
devices we can carry around
on ourselves to measure

00:15:01.700 --> 00:15:04.300
everything we do.

00:15:04.300 --> 00:15:06.640
I got into social media
a long time ago.

00:15:06.640 --> 00:15:07.610
I mean, now I'm not.

00:15:07.610 --> 00:15:09.570
We don't even say we're into
social media, that's not cool.

00:15:09.570 --> 00:15:12.360
But back in like 2006 and 2007,
when things were really

00:15:12.360 --> 00:15:15.080
starting to heat up again with
blogs, and Twitter was coming

00:15:15.080 --> 00:15:17.800
on to the fore, and we were
all watching our follower

00:15:17.800 --> 00:15:19.740
count, and our friend number,
and all that stuff.

00:15:19.740 --> 00:15:22.550
And there's all these numbers
that are around us.

00:15:22.550 --> 00:15:26.370
And if you find that you're
checking statistics all the

00:15:26.370 --> 00:15:29.310
time, regardless of what
statistics they are, think

00:15:29.310 --> 00:15:31.450
about whether it's something
that is a key performance

00:15:31.450 --> 00:15:34.200
indicator for the value of your
work or something you're

00:15:34.200 --> 00:15:35.830
trying to change in your life.

00:15:35.830 --> 00:15:38.310
Because if it's not, there's a
good chance it's more just

00:15:38.310 --> 00:15:39.240
weighing you down.

00:15:39.240 --> 00:15:41.490
And maybe it makes you feel good
when you get that extra

00:15:41.490 --> 00:15:44.670
number or maybe it makes you
feel awful, but if it doesn't

00:15:44.670 --> 00:15:47.560
really change something in your
life or in your work,

00:15:47.560 --> 00:15:50.610
maybe you should just
stop checking it.

00:15:50.610 --> 00:15:52.080
There's probably a lot
of numbers around.

00:15:52.080 --> 00:15:54.130
You think about which ones
you can let go of.

00:15:54.130 --> 00:15:56.980
Maybe do it once a week or
maybe set a Cron job that

00:15:56.980 --> 00:15:59.200
sends it to you once a week so
you don't have to check it

00:15:59.200 --> 00:16:00.530
every three hours if
there's been new

00:16:00.530 --> 00:16:03.860
sign ups on your product.

00:16:03.860 --> 00:16:05.770
Another thing, it's called
the Pomodoro

00:16:05.770 --> 00:16:07.360
Technique or Pomodoro Method.

00:16:07.360 --> 00:16:09.350
I see a lot of folks here
are familiar with that.

00:16:09.350 --> 00:16:12.880
It's the idea of getting
yourself into something for 50

00:16:12.880 --> 00:16:17.400
minutes and focusing on it and
then moving on for about 10

00:16:17.400 --> 00:16:21.250
minutes and maybe going to one
of your mini cafes, or talking

00:16:21.250 --> 00:16:24.060
to someone, or having some
other kind of challenge.

00:16:24.060 --> 00:16:27.290
You can google Pomodoro, like
the type of tomato.

00:16:27.290 --> 00:16:28.580
And this is just one
of the techniques.

00:16:28.580 --> 00:16:30.590
I'm going to go into flow
a little bit more.

00:16:30.590 --> 00:16:33.420
But this is just one of the many
concepts I think that's

00:16:33.420 --> 00:16:34.980
worth researching if
you're getting into

00:16:34.980 --> 00:16:37.870
this type of material.

00:16:37.870 --> 00:16:41.870
We've got folks here from the +
team, and I love your little

00:16:41.870 --> 00:16:43.780
notification that pops
up all the time.

00:16:43.780 --> 00:16:50.340
But we as people who are
knowledge workers, we do have

00:16:50.340 --> 00:16:53.350
other responsibilities besides
the main task at hand.

00:16:53.350 --> 00:16:55.910
And in that 10 minutes or in
that time that you dedicate to

00:16:55.910 --> 00:16:59.370
doing social media or keeping
up with other things, I'd

00:16:59.370 --> 00:17:02.250
recommend going 100%
into those things.

00:17:02.250 --> 00:17:06.230
Jump into that stream of social
media, or of analytics,

00:17:06.230 --> 00:17:08.520
or whatever it happens to be,
and then get out of it.

00:17:08.520 --> 00:17:10.630
As opposed to having the little
alerts that pop up at

00:17:10.630 --> 00:17:11.200
different times.

00:17:11.200 --> 00:17:13.690
This is just like with email,
but with other things.

00:17:13.690 --> 00:17:18.329
It's OK to have distractions,
but I recommend batching them,

00:17:18.329 --> 00:17:19.410
putting them in one
little place.

00:17:19.410 --> 00:17:24.240
Jump into that stream, and
then jump out of it.

00:17:24.240 --> 00:17:25.500
And also unplug.

00:17:25.500 --> 00:17:27.079
I mentioned making
a giant list.

00:17:27.079 --> 00:17:29.420
I mentioned pressing Archive
All to get a

00:17:29.420 --> 00:17:31.670
little bit more clarity.

00:17:31.670 --> 00:17:35.020
But it's amazing, I bought
the most expensive

00:17:35.020 --> 00:17:36.290
paper I could buy.

00:17:36.290 --> 00:17:41.400
I think it was $15 for 108
brightness and 32 pound paper,

00:17:41.400 --> 00:17:42.760
whatever it happens to be.

00:17:42.760 --> 00:17:45.790
But it is liberating to just
have that sheet of paper and

00:17:45.790 --> 00:17:47.120
get those ideas out.

00:17:47.120 --> 00:17:48.720
It's true, there's going to be
periods where you have to

00:17:48.720 --> 00:17:53.020
spend 6, or 20, or 50 hours over
a certain period of time

00:17:53.020 --> 00:17:56.090
writing an article or coding a
particular module, whatever it

00:17:56.090 --> 00:17:57.190
happens to be.

00:17:57.190 --> 00:17:59.170
But there are times where you
really just need clarity and

00:17:59.170 --> 00:18:02.380
there's just something to be
said for paper or turning off

00:18:02.380 --> 00:18:03.760
the internet.

00:18:03.760 --> 00:18:06.050
So try to add that into
your routine.

00:18:06.050 --> 00:18:09.870
Anybody ever been productive on
a train or a plane before?

00:18:09.870 --> 00:18:12.150
Why not recreate that one
hour of every day, that

00:18:12.150 --> 00:18:13.620
opportunity?

00:18:13.620 --> 00:18:16.480
In my mornings, I try to have
a bit of time every day

00:18:16.480 --> 00:18:18.020
without internet activity.

00:18:18.020 --> 00:18:20.740
And it's amazing what you can
get done in that period.

00:18:20.740 --> 00:18:23.050
Even if you have a few sites you
need for that work, just

00:18:23.050 --> 00:18:26.360
bring them up and in a tab in
Chrome, and then do the other

00:18:26.360 --> 00:18:28.250
stuff, and you have
them there.

00:18:28.250 --> 00:18:30.070
And even make a list for the
things you're going to have to

00:18:30.070 --> 00:18:30.950
do when you're back online.

00:18:30.950 --> 00:18:33.870
But it's amazing what you'll
get done a little bit when

00:18:33.870 --> 00:18:35.030
you're offline.

00:18:35.030 --> 00:18:36.500
Plus, you have your phones
and a million

00:18:36.500 --> 00:18:38.190
other ways to connect.

00:18:38.190 --> 00:18:40.090
I even like taking this further
and creating what I

00:18:40.090 --> 00:18:43.500
like to call a "cone of
silence." This idea that you

00:18:43.500 --> 00:18:46.590
literally just have one thing
you're super focused on.

00:18:46.590 --> 00:18:50.520
And I know I keep drilling
into this point.

00:18:50.520 --> 00:18:53.560
But it's interesting
with email.

00:18:53.560 --> 00:18:56.710
Most of us consume it at various
points in our day and

00:18:56.710 --> 00:18:58.600
probably various points
in an hour.

00:18:58.600 --> 00:19:01.910
I think studies range between
18 to 36 times per hour.

00:19:01.910 --> 00:19:04.430
You guys have much better
data on that, I'm sure.

00:19:04.430 --> 00:19:07.910
But that was in the most recent
Gloria Mark study.

00:19:07.910 --> 00:19:09.370
They referenced that.

00:19:09.370 --> 00:19:11.830
That's a lot of time to
constantly check your email.

00:19:11.830 --> 00:19:13.880
That means that any given one
task you're doing, you're

00:19:13.880 --> 00:19:15.750
spending less than four
minutes on it.

00:19:15.750 --> 00:19:18.890
The truth is, though, if you
make email your job, if you

00:19:18.890 --> 00:19:22.450
literally say, for the next 45
minutes I'm going to do email,

00:19:22.450 --> 00:19:24.600
you will get through what you
need to get through in there.

00:19:24.600 --> 00:19:26.690
You'll be able to process it,
create tasks from it.

00:19:26.690 --> 00:19:28.480
You can all watch the
Inbox Zero talk

00:19:28.480 --> 00:19:29.540
that was Merlin Mann.

00:19:29.540 --> 00:19:31.270
You probably have all seen
it, that he did here.

00:19:31.270 --> 00:19:32.890
It's a great way to learn
all the processing

00:19:32.890 --> 00:19:33.880
techniques for email.

00:19:33.880 --> 00:19:36.400
But if you give yourself 40
minutes to really get into

00:19:36.400 --> 00:19:41.200
that inbox, or really get into
that article, or that UX

00:19:41.200 --> 00:19:44.370
workflow, or whatever it happens
to be, it's insane

00:19:44.370 --> 00:19:45.350
what you can get out of it.

00:19:45.350 --> 00:19:48.030
And I know, again, I'm stressing
the same point, but

00:19:48.030 --> 00:19:50.360
give yourself that cone of
silence and you will do

00:19:50.360 --> 00:19:53.180
something amazing with
that period of time.

00:19:53.180 --> 00:19:55.490
Also, think about the essential
and the incidental.

00:19:55.490 --> 00:19:58.390
There's a URL here,
bit.ly/thecriticalpath.

00:19:58.390 --> 00:20:00.430
And I have a whole article that
I talk about how to write

00:20:00.430 --> 00:20:01.630
out a sheet of paper and
figure out what your

00:20:01.630 --> 00:20:02.790
critical path is.

00:20:02.790 --> 00:20:06.660
But the concept of critical path
refers to at the end of

00:20:06.660 --> 00:20:10.050
this year, at the end of this
quarter, or just in my life,

00:20:10.050 --> 00:20:12.580
here's something that really,
really needs to happen.

00:20:12.580 --> 00:20:15.140
Maybe it's that we get a million
users, maybe it's that

00:20:15.140 --> 00:20:17.800
we increase adoption by this
percent, maybe it's that we

00:20:17.800 --> 00:20:19.860
bring on this many brands to
our product, whatever it

00:20:19.860 --> 00:20:20.990
happens to be.

00:20:20.990 --> 00:20:24.420
But if you look at your task
list, that giant list you have

00:20:24.420 --> 00:20:27.390
of 100 plus items, I will bet
you that most of those things,

00:20:27.390 --> 00:20:30.010
probably more than half of them,
won't actually relate to

00:20:30.010 --> 00:20:31.810
that specific goal.

00:20:31.810 --> 00:20:34.680
And that's what's fascinating is
we have this critical path

00:20:34.680 --> 00:20:36.290
and most things aren't on it.

00:20:36.290 --> 00:20:39.120
And then all of a sudden it gets
really easy if you say to

00:20:39.120 --> 00:20:41.500
yourself, in the mornings, I'm
never going to do something

00:20:41.500 --> 00:20:43.080
that's not on my
critical path.

00:20:43.080 --> 00:20:45.040
I know I have to respond to
emails, I know there's this

00:20:45.040 --> 00:20:47.150
birthday thing coming up, I
know there's these talks I

00:20:47.150 --> 00:20:47.645
want to see.

00:20:47.645 --> 00:20:49.450
But in my mornings, I'm only
going to do things on my

00:20:49.450 --> 00:20:52.000
critical path.

00:20:52.000 --> 00:20:54.780
And amazingly, you will
get forward with it.

00:20:54.780 --> 00:20:57.070
It's just like the whole if you
spend 30 minutes a day on

00:20:57.070 --> 00:20:59.780
something forever, you're going
to be the world's expert

00:20:59.780 --> 00:21:01.630
in that thing or one of.

00:21:01.630 --> 00:21:04.250
So consider what is incidental
and what is

00:21:04.250 --> 00:21:06.050
essential, what is critical.

00:21:06.050 --> 00:21:07.760
And try to fill your
day as much as

00:21:07.760 --> 00:21:08.630
possible with those things.

00:21:08.630 --> 00:21:12.300
It's a really great heuristic
for limiting tasks.

00:21:12.300 --> 00:21:14.570
And then circadian rhythms.

00:21:14.570 --> 00:21:16.690
This is one of these concepts
that sounds kind of

00:21:16.690 --> 00:21:17.600
loosey-goosey, I don't know.

00:21:17.600 --> 00:21:19.435
Like I have different
flow states at

00:21:19.435 --> 00:21:19.900
different times of day.

00:21:19.900 --> 00:21:22.960
But the reality is, if you
think about it, you have

00:21:22.960 --> 00:21:25.700
different energy levels at
different times of the day.

00:21:25.700 --> 00:21:28.750
And if you have the ability to
manipulate your schedule a

00:21:28.750 --> 00:21:31.640
little bit, you can structure
it so that you do the right

00:21:31.640 --> 00:21:33.450
work for that energy level.

00:21:33.450 --> 00:21:34.440
So for me, what does
that mean?

00:21:34.440 --> 00:21:37.000
It means that I don't do
meetings before lunch.

00:21:37.000 --> 00:21:37.710
Why is that?

00:21:37.710 --> 00:21:41.710
It's because I have energy and
I have focus at that time,

00:21:41.710 --> 00:21:42.990
before lunch that is.

00:21:42.990 --> 00:21:46.220
I do my most creative
work before lunch.

00:21:46.220 --> 00:21:47.140
And that's amazing for me.

00:21:47.140 --> 00:21:49.440
Now when I'm sitting down in
a meeting, particularly if

00:21:49.440 --> 00:21:51.600
there's a cup of coffee or
something, I mean I am going

00:21:51.600 --> 00:21:52.340
to have no trouble.

00:21:52.340 --> 00:21:54.580
If I'm sitting with Gopi at 3:00
in the afternoon, he has

00:21:54.580 --> 00:21:56.190
my attention, I'm never
going to mess that up.

00:21:56.190 --> 00:22:00.100
But if I'm sitting with an
article to write or a spec to

00:22:00.100 --> 00:22:02.390
draw out, I'm going to find
everything else to do, and I'm

00:22:02.390 --> 00:22:04.810
going to be completely all over
the place because I don't

00:22:04.810 --> 00:22:07.420
have the same attention
in the afternoons.

00:22:07.420 --> 00:22:11.110
So think about how your day
works and your energy levels,

00:22:11.110 --> 00:22:13.040
and see if there's a way you
can adapt your day a

00:22:13.040 --> 00:22:14.320
little bit to it.

00:22:14.320 --> 00:22:17.240
And along the same line, just
walking down the cafeteria

00:22:17.240 --> 00:22:20.890
here I see lots of people eating
food that who knows if

00:22:20.890 --> 00:22:22.520
it's the best thing for them
to be eating right now in

00:22:22.520 --> 00:22:23.990
terms of giving themself
energy for

00:22:23.990 --> 00:22:24.440
the rest of the day.

00:22:24.440 --> 00:22:27.100
But think about how the
food you consume

00:22:27.100 --> 00:22:28.350
relates to your energy.

00:22:28.350 --> 00:22:32.260
For me, for example, I do all
protein in the morning and

00:22:32.260 --> 00:22:33.750
just about all protein
in the afternoon.

00:22:33.750 --> 00:22:35.010
Or rather, I don't
touch carbs.

00:22:35.010 --> 00:22:37.090
It's not that I do
all protein.

00:22:37.090 --> 00:22:38.960
And by cutting carbs out
of my morning and my

00:22:38.960 --> 00:22:41.290
afternoon, it's amazing.

00:22:41.290 --> 00:22:42.960
When I used to eat cereal or
bagels in morning, which I

00:22:42.960 --> 00:22:46.850
loved, I would be tired
or at like 10:30 or

00:22:46.850 --> 00:22:47.760
11:00 I'd be hungry.

00:22:47.760 --> 00:22:50.240
And I'm not saying that's the
solution for you, but it's

00:22:50.240 --> 00:22:53.590
amazing how we really are slaves
to our bodies and we

00:22:53.590 --> 00:22:57.900
can really schedule our days and
consider our intakes based

00:22:57.900 --> 00:23:00.850
on these kinds of things.

00:23:00.850 --> 00:23:04.170
And this is actually
my last slide here.

00:23:04.170 --> 00:23:06.280
It's coming near the
end of the year.

00:23:06.280 --> 00:23:09.950
And it's one of those times
where we start looking back

00:23:09.950 --> 00:23:11.550
and thinking about the things
we've accomplished.

00:23:11.550 --> 00:23:13.190
And I've been doing a
bit of that lately.

00:23:15.700 --> 00:23:17.380
Maybe this won't come as a
surprise, but I've realized

00:23:17.380 --> 00:23:21.415
the things that have made the
biggest impact on my company

00:23:21.415 --> 00:23:24.740
and upon myself, there's
two things about them.

00:23:24.740 --> 00:23:29.160
One is that those things were
never assigned to me.

00:23:29.160 --> 00:23:30.220
Nobody told me to do that.

00:23:30.220 --> 00:23:33.690
My investors, my board,
my team, friends

00:23:33.690 --> 00:23:34.820
didn't suggest it.

00:23:34.820 --> 00:23:37.150
I'm sure you've probably seen
that users of your products

00:23:37.150 --> 00:23:39.970
rarely suggest the things that
are the best features because

00:23:39.970 --> 00:23:41.440
they're not in it
the same way.

00:23:41.440 --> 00:23:43.780
Maybe they are, but generally
speaking, they're thinking one

00:23:43.780 --> 00:23:46.480
step out and you're thinking
four steps out.

00:23:46.480 --> 00:23:48.660
And for me, I found that, again,
those things weren't

00:23:48.660 --> 00:23:49.590
assigned to me.

00:23:49.590 --> 00:23:52.230
And similarly, they were
the things where I had

00:23:52.230 --> 00:23:54.890
to put in 100 hours.

00:23:54.890 --> 00:23:56.430
Even though I probably could
have done that same thing in

00:23:56.430 --> 00:23:58.550
10 hours and it would've
been OK.

00:23:58.550 --> 00:24:02.070
So there's a lot of things in
your job that you do that you

00:24:02.070 --> 00:24:04.950
do good enough, you maybe even
do it really well because

00:24:04.950 --> 00:24:06.230
you're just a smart person.

00:24:06.230 --> 00:24:07.710
Everybody in this room, I'm
sure, is incredibly

00:24:07.710 --> 00:24:08.580
intelligent.

00:24:08.580 --> 00:24:12.970
And then there's other things,
though, that you probably know

00:24:12.970 --> 00:24:15.720
you could either do it better
or, even more, it's the area

00:24:15.720 --> 00:24:17.250
where you are just
like the best.

00:24:17.250 --> 00:24:19.240
There's something where you're
in the 99 point something

00:24:19.240 --> 00:24:20.880
percentile.

00:24:20.880 --> 00:24:23.770
And when you do those things,
you've probably found that you

00:24:23.770 --> 00:24:25.940
can get amazing results
with that.

00:24:25.940 --> 00:24:28.810
So when I write like my guide to
not checking email, it was

00:24:28.810 --> 00:24:30.120
just something that nobody
told me to do.

00:24:30.120 --> 00:24:33.730
And it got amazing, amazing
attention from it.

00:24:33.730 --> 00:24:35.850
There's certain things that
I've done in my life, like

00:24:35.850 --> 00:24:38.420
when I wrote the guide to
Outlook versus Gmail, that,

00:24:38.420 --> 00:24:41.070
back in the day, got hundreds of
thousands of views and made

00:24:41.070 --> 00:24:41.830
it to the front page of Digg.

00:24:41.830 --> 00:24:45.230
And it was this giant article
that was a big risk for me,

00:24:45.230 --> 00:24:47.270
but I put everything into it.

00:24:47.270 --> 00:24:49.710
And every time I've put
everything into something,

00:24:49.710 --> 00:24:52.280
I've got insane results back.

00:24:52.280 --> 00:24:54.580
So when you think about your
to-do lists, think about

00:24:54.580 --> 00:24:56.990
what's not on your to-do
list and think about

00:24:56.990 --> 00:24:58.190
what you're best at.

00:24:58.190 --> 00:25:01.360
And maybe you can do something
that's remarkable as opposed

00:25:01.360 --> 00:25:03.090
to something that's
just productive.

00:25:03.090 --> 00:25:06.070
Hopefully with fluency in these
tools, you can free up a

00:25:06.070 --> 00:25:07.360
little bit of time
in your days.

00:25:07.360 --> 00:25:10.370
Maybe you have that 20% time,
maybe it feels like you have

00:25:10.370 --> 00:25:11.920
the 20% percent time
but don't.

00:25:11.920 --> 00:25:15.200
But if you can have that time to
do something that is going

00:25:15.200 --> 00:25:18.770
to scale, I think you'll
be amazed with what

00:25:18.770 --> 00:25:20.570
comes out of it.

