00:27:36.160 --> 00:27:37.775
So I know in GTD they
talk about context.

00:27:37.775 --> 00:27:39.530
They say you should have your
list for when you're in your

00:27:39.530 --> 00:27:41.100
car, or your home, or
different things.

00:27:41.100 --> 00:27:41.860
I don't do all of that.

00:27:41.860 --> 00:27:44.570
I just have a list of things
that I'm actually really going

00:27:44.570 --> 00:27:47.440
to do, or that I actually
have to do today.

00:27:47.440 --> 00:27:49.730
And then I have a list of things
that I need to do that

00:27:49.730 --> 00:27:51.380
I really do need to do.

00:27:51.380 --> 00:27:53.930
And then I just have this giant
list that someday maybe.

00:27:53.930 --> 00:27:57.140
And the soon list, I
look at every week.

00:27:57.140 --> 00:28:00.120
It's probably like
45, 50 items.

00:28:00.120 --> 00:28:02.860
The today list, I take
some things from it.

00:28:02.860 --> 00:28:04.660
And it doesn't mean that I
always get them done today.

00:28:04.660 --> 00:28:06.600
But it never gets to more
than like 10 items.

00:28:06.600 --> 00:28:09.720
I try to keep it more like
three or four items.

00:28:09.720 --> 00:28:12.790
So I have my things that
I really have to do.

00:28:12.790 --> 00:28:15.550
I have the things that I hope
to really do today.

00:28:15.550 --> 00:28:17.700
And then I have this giant
list that I might look at

00:28:17.700 --> 00:28:18.810
every month or so.

00:28:18.810 --> 00:28:22.560
And when I'm going through soon,
sometimes I move it to

00:28:22.560 --> 00:28:24.890
the forever, who knows,
whatever list,

00:28:24.890 --> 00:28:26.440
and sometimes I don't.

00:28:26.440 --> 00:28:29.060
I do have other lists, but
they're more lists of

00:28:29.060 --> 00:28:31.820
restaurants, or movies, or
people's names I don't want to

00:28:31.820 --> 00:28:32.780
forget, things like that.

00:28:32.780 --> 00:28:35.350
I try to keep those off of the
things that are actionable and

00:28:35.350 --> 00:28:36.660
that I have to really
pay attention to.

00:28:36.660 --> 00:28:38.020
Because those I actually will
go back to look at.

00:28:38.020 --> 00:28:39.910
You know, I walk into the coffee
house, I'm like, I know

00:28:39.910 --> 00:28:41.560
I know that person, I'm
going to look that up.

00:28:41.560 --> 00:28:44.340
Like that's me accessing
it that way.

00:28:44.340 --> 00:28:47.120
But I really try to keep the
actionable, necessary stuff.

00:28:47.120 --> 00:28:50.488
Those are the only things I
look at on a weekly basis.

00:28:50.488 --> 00:28:53.740
AUDIENCE: So what are your tips
for when you work with

00:28:53.740 --> 00:28:56.460
systems like GTD and
to-do lists?

00:28:56.460 --> 00:29:02.130
How do you not let it focus you
on the small tasks and do

00:29:02.130 --> 00:29:05.850
something bigger?

00:29:05.850 --> 00:29:07.490
JARED GORALNICK: Well, it
helps to know what your

00:29:07.490 --> 00:29:09.910
critical path is.

00:29:09.910 --> 00:29:11.130
What is one of the
most important

00:29:11.130 --> 00:29:11.980
things for your work?

00:29:11.980 --> 00:29:16.470
AUDIENCE: What I noticed, when
I really try and get into

00:29:16.470 --> 00:29:20.970
these productivity systems, they
take your attention away

00:29:20.970 --> 00:29:25.110
from the big picture and
onto these little

00:29:25.110 --> 00:29:26.600
chunks, little tasks.

00:29:26.600 --> 00:29:30.990
These little tasks are very
optimized to do efficiently

00:29:30.990 --> 00:29:33.150
and be productive
on that level.

00:29:33.150 --> 00:29:36.940
But at the end of the day, all
you have is a list of these

00:29:36.940 --> 00:29:40.350
small little tasks that you've
done and not your

00:29:40.350 --> 00:29:41.880
big project, maybe.

00:29:41.880 --> 00:29:43.950
So I wonder what your
suggestions are.

00:29:43.950 --> 00:29:47.350
How do you keep the focus on
the big picture while using

00:29:47.350 --> 00:29:47.930
those systems?

00:29:47.930 --> 00:29:48.930
JARED GORALNICK: So I
think there's two

00:29:48.930 --> 00:29:50.330
components to that.

00:29:50.330 --> 00:29:52.490
One component of it is the
fact that you have

00:29:52.490 --> 00:29:53.350
some sort of review.

00:29:53.350 --> 00:29:55.170
Like the evening before you
spend like literally two

00:29:55.170 --> 00:29:55.910
minutes and you're
like, what do I

00:29:55.910 --> 00:29:56.940
want to get done tomorrow?

00:29:56.940 --> 00:29:59.590
So you have some idea about what
is on the big project you

00:29:59.590 --> 00:30:00.790
want to do.

00:30:00.790 --> 00:30:03.670
And the second part of it is,
and this is where some people,

00:30:03.670 --> 00:30:06.390
I think, make the mistake of
when to use a calendar versus

00:30:06.390 --> 00:30:07.900
when to use a task.

00:30:07.900 --> 00:30:09.950
You shouldn't put all your
tasks in your calendar.

00:30:09.950 --> 00:30:11.690
You all know probably the basic
why you don't but your

00:30:11.690 --> 00:30:12.600
tasks in your calendar.

00:30:12.600 --> 00:30:14.470
It's because the next day, if
you didn't do it, it's now

00:30:14.470 --> 00:30:15.430
disappeared.

00:30:15.430 --> 00:30:17.020
But the task didn't disappear.

00:30:17.020 --> 00:30:19.170
So that's why you don't
just use your calendar

00:30:19.170 --> 00:30:19.770
for your task list.

00:30:19.770 --> 00:30:22.840
However, that's why I
was suggesting how I

00:30:22.840 --> 00:30:24.110
