00:30:51.080 --> 00:30:53.930
You know, a bunch of phone
calls, and silly phone calls

00:30:53.930 --> 00:30:56.160
too, not even really important
work meeting phone calls.

00:30:56.160 --> 00:30:58.980
I try to batch those.

00:30:58.980 --> 00:31:00.450
I had a postcard the other
day I picked up.

00:31:00.450 --> 00:31:01.740
I should have brought it and put
it on this presentation.

00:31:01.740 --> 00:31:04.080
Something like, I can't do any
big things because I'm always

00:31:04.080 --> 00:31:05.800
spending time on the
little things.

00:31:05.800 --> 00:31:09.055
So you need to block out
those big things.

00:31:09.055 --> 00:31:11.660
You don't have to necessarily
put it in your calendar, but

00:31:11.660 --> 00:31:14.800
really just make sure that you
know every day when you're

00:31:14.800 --> 00:31:15.370
going to being do that.

00:31:15.370 --> 00:31:18.330
Because if you don't do that,
you're never going to feel

00:31:18.330 --> 00:31:19.780
like you accomplished
anything.

00:31:19.780 --> 00:31:21.270
And people say to do it
first thing in the

00:31:21.270 --> 00:31:22.050
morning if you can.

00:31:22.050 --> 00:31:23.850
I like doing that, some
people don't.

00:31:23.850 --> 00:31:26.430
But if you do the major, major
important stuff first thing,

00:31:26.430 --> 00:31:28.940
what's great about it is then
all the stuff that piled up

00:31:28.940 --> 00:31:32.480
from your inbox and the other
tasks you have to do, you can

00:31:32.480 --> 00:31:34.180
deal with them the rest of the
day, but at least you got

00:31:34.180 --> 00:31:37.220
something really major
done that morning.

00:31:37.220 --> 00:31:40.620
AUDIENCE: So what I've noticed
about new organizational

00:31:40.620 --> 00:31:42.800
systems, new management systems,
is that it's not so

00:31:42.800 --> 00:31:44.582
much the things that you already
know to do, it's the

00:31:44.582 --> 00:31:47.020
things that you don't know
that you have to do, the

00:31:47.020 --> 00:31:49.000
sudden interruption, the sudden
high priority thing

00:31:49.000 --> 00:31:52.260
that you did not accommodate
or plan for.

00:31:52.260 --> 00:31:54.940
Like you get sick or something
major happens and it blows

00:31:54.940 --> 00:31:56.690
apart your priorities.

00:31:56.690 --> 00:31:59.660
And therefore, once that
disruption happens, you can't

00:31:59.660 --> 00:32:02.960
recover back, so you sort
of just go on the

00:32:02.960 --> 00:32:03.550
way you used to.

00:32:03.550 --> 00:32:05.540
How do you handle that?

00:32:05.540 --> 00:32:07.040
JARED GORALNICK: Well, that's
the beauty of having a

00:32:07.040 --> 00:32:09.360
shorter task list.

00:32:09.360 --> 00:32:11.790
And what I mean by that is
like if you have that now

00:32:11.790 --> 00:32:15.150
list, then today when you get
sick or somebody comes in with

00:32:15.150 --> 00:32:17.190
a real emergency, yeah,
your day is screwed.

00:32:17.190 --> 00:32:19.760
Like I can't fix the problem
where you have seven hours

00:32:19.760 --> 00:32:21.140
worth of stuff to
do in four hours

00:32:21.140 --> 00:32:23.340
today, it can't be fixed.

00:32:23.340 --> 00:32:27.580
But if that next day, before
you start your day or

00:32:27.580 --> 00:32:29.070
whatever, you are going
to recalibrate and

00:32:29.070 --> 00:32:29.910
say, you know what?

00:32:29.910 --> 00:32:31.080
I'm just not going to be
able to do that thing.

00:32:31.080 --> 00:32:32.970
I'm even going to tell him
that I can't finish

00:32:32.970 --> 00:32:34.180
that thing on time.

00:32:34.180 --> 00:32:37.140
If you give yourself that
opportunity every day to set

00:32:37.140 --> 00:32:39.720
what your task list is for the
next day, then when you would

00:32:39.720 --> 00:32:44.690
get one of these catastrophic
things, you are able to just

00:32:44.690 --> 00:32:46.640
manipulate what you're doing
the next day as opposed to

00:32:46.640 --> 00:32:49.470
just having this list of 100
things and now you just never

00:32:49.470 --> 00:32:51.780
get to look at the other 99
because you just have one

00:32:51.780 --> 00:32:52.690
that's at the top.

00:32:52.690 --> 00:32:54.820
Now, this may sound like I'm
just saying I'm skirting

00:32:54.820 --> 00:32:55.830
around the problem.

00:32:55.830 --> 00:32:58.580
But I really think most of this
stuff is psychological.

00:32:58.580 --> 00:33:02.390
And what I mean by that is like
when crises happen, we

00:33:02.390 --> 00:33:04.320
always get through it.

00:33:04.320 --> 00:33:07.200
It's up to us, though, of
whether during that crisis we

00:33:07.200 --> 00:33:09.860
want to also feel overwhelmed
by every single time we look

00:33:09.860 --> 00:33:12.380
at the place, whether it be our
inbox or our task list,

00:33:12.380 --> 00:33:14.670
that sort of dictates how we
should be spending our time.

00:33:14.670 --> 00:33:17.060
If every time we look at that
we're also overwhelmed.

00:33:17.060 --> 00:33:21.030
So if you can respect yourself
enough to say that if I make

00:33:21.030 --> 00:33:23.990
it out of sight, out of mind,
I'm going to live with that,

00:33:23.990 --> 00:33:25.870
then you'll make some hard
decisions and move some things

00:33:25.870 --> 00:33:28.500
off your today list into
the soon list.

00:33:28.500 --> 00:33:30.900
And just accept that certain
things won't get done.

00:33:30.900 --> 00:33:34.310
But it's better to tell yourself
I'm not going to do

00:33:34.310 --> 00:33:38.500
this then to try to just pretend
that adding a bunch of

00:33:38.500 --> 00:33:40.750
crazy stuff into your list is
somehow going to happen.

00:33:40.750 --> 00:33:44.110
Because all you can do
with that is time.

00:33:44.110 --> 00:33:45.970
You have to say no
to some things.

00:33:45.970 --> 00:33:48.180
But I think the best way to say
no to that is every day to

00:33:48.180 --> 00:33:51.550
have a little bit of a conscious
decision about what

00:33:51.550 --> 00:33:54.480
you want to accomplish
that day or the next.

00:33:54.480 --> 00:33:57.570
